    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The fine print can be a minefield, and it's not uncommon for lawyers to use clever wordplay or technicalities to catch people off guard. One common tactic is to use \"catch-all\" clauses, which can include a wide range of potential risks or damages. These clauses might say something like \"any and all losses\" or \"any and all claims,\" without specifying exactly what those losses or claims might look like.\n\nAnother technique is to rely on judicial interpretations of existing laws or precedents, which can be unclear or open to multiple interpretations. This can create a situation where a clause that seems innocuous on the surface can actually have far-reaching consequences. It's not necessarily \"predatory,\" but rather a reflection of the complexities and nuances of contract law.",
